%% 英文摘要 %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\BiAppendixChapter{Abstract}{Abstract (In English)}

Radiation hydrodynamics has a wide range of applications in scientific and technological fields such as inertial confinement fusion, plasma physics, high-temperature fluid mechanics, and astrophysics. It is a crucial problem to design efficient and high order accurate numerical methods to solve the radiation hydrodynamics models. However, the exchange of momentum and energy between the radiation and the matter affects the motion of the fluid. Especially under high temperature conditions, radiation energy takes a dominant status in the total energy, making numerical simulation of radiation hydrodynamics challenging at present.

In response to the need of numerical simulation of radiation hydrodynamics, this thesis studies one-dimensional and two-dimensional radiation hydrodynamics models (radiation hydrodynamics model in equilibrium diffusion limit and radiation hydrodynamics model in gray non-equilibrium diffusion limit), and the dissipation problem for the related convection-diffusion equations.
For the radiation hydrodynamics model, we split the system into two subsystems to solve. One part is the hyperbolic part which couples the radiation field and the fluid, and the other part is the parabolic part which evolves the radiation diffusion.
For the hyperbolic part of the subsystem, we use the MUSCL-Hancock scheme to solve, and at the same time, we use the implicit method to solve the diffusion subsystem.
For radiation hydrodynamics model under gray non-equilibrium diffusion limit, we introduce the radiative entropy equation. Compared with the direct IMEX (implicit-explicit scheme) method, our scheme calculates weaker nonlinear implicit equations at each time step.
For the calculation of implicit equations, we use the Newton-BiCGSTAB algorithm, which can avoid solving and storing the Jacobian matrix. For the dissipation problem of the convection-diffusion equations, we apply the GRP algorithm to solve it.
This also makes it possible to apply the algorithm to the radiation fluid dynamics model. Numerical experiments show the performance of the above model algorithms, and the numerical experimental results of the radiation fluid mechanics model are consistent with the theory of radiation shock solutions, which proves the effectiveness of the algorithm.
